  "notes": "Kabardian (къэбэрдей адыгэбзэ, East Circassian) — Northwest Caucasian, written in a Cyrillic alphabet since 1936 (Latin and Arabic orthographies are historical/diaspora and are not modelled). INPUT CONTRACT: Cyrillic text in the standard Kabardian orthography, Unicode NFC; the palochka is expected as U+04CF ⟨ӏ⟩ (lowercase) / U+04C0 ⟨Ӏ⟩ (uppercase), not ASCII I/l/1. The orthography is overwhelmingly DIGRAPHIC and TRIGRAPHIC: ⟨ъ⟩ (uvular/back series), ⟨ӏ⟩ (ejective/glottal) and ⟨у⟩ (labialisation) combine with a base letter to spell single phonemes — гъ, гъу, къ, къу, кхъ, кхъу, кӏ, кӏу, лъ, лӏ, пӏ, тӏ, фӏ, хь, хъ, хъу, ху, цӏ, щӏ, ӏу — and each is a grapheme key of its own, matched by maximal munch (longest key wins, so кхъу beats кхъ beats къ). Phonemic vowels are ⟨э⟩ /a/, ⟨а⟩ /aː/, ⟨ы⟩ /ə/; ⟨е и о у ю я ё⟩ spell glide+vowel sequences and take their surface values from the alphabet table. ⟨дж⟩ and ⟨кӏ⟩ have dialectal double values, both listed (best first). The modifier letters ⟨ъ⟩ /ˠ/ and ⟨ь⟩ /ʲ/ occur only as parts of digraphs in native words and are given no standalone entry.",
